WEBVTT

00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:04.000
<v Speaker 1>Spanish dialects don't change very much.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.800
<v Speaker 1>Slang changes a lot, but Spanish is pretty standard.

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:11.120
<v Speaker 1>It's not like Arabic, for example, where you have such a different Arabic in Morocco.

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:12.780
<v Speaker 1>to Egypt for example.

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:17.740
<v Speaker 1>All of the different Spanishes are completely mutually intelligible.

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:22.700
<v Speaker 1>But in slang you get many different uh terms and words.

00:00:22.619 --> 00:00:25.980
<v Speaker 1>And car is one of these words that have different versions.

00:00:25.980 --> 00:00:27.259
<v Speaker 1>Money is another one.

00:00:27.259 --> 00:00:30.779
<v Speaker 1>You might hear dinero, which is like the standard word.

00:00:30.779 --> 00:00:34.699
<v Speaker 1>You might hear plata, which actually means silver.

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:39.040
<v Speaker 1>Pasta, you might hear pasta, that's one, they use that in Spain.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:41.440
<v Speaker 1>So we had a few words for car.

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:43.360
<v Speaker 1>Do you remember any of them?

00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:46.260
<v Speaker 2>Um machina auto?

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:47.300
<v Speaker 2>Caro?

00:00:47.300 --> 00:00:48.260
<v Speaker 1>Carro.

00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:49.059
<v Speaker 1>Carro.

00:00:49.059 --> 00:00:49.379
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:49.379 --> 00:00:50.340
<v Speaker 1>Two hours.

00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:51.940
<v Speaker 1>Let's stay with carro.

00:00:51.940 --> 00:00:54.500
<v Speaker 1>How would you say the car?

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:56.160
<v Speaker 2>El carro.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:57.120
<v Speaker 1>El carro.

00:00:57.120 --> 00:00:59.360
<v Speaker 1>And how would you say a car?

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:00.720
<v Speaker 2>Uncarro.

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:01.680
<v Speaker 1>Uncarro.

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:02.000
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.560
<v Speaker 1>So it's a masculine word and we use el for the and un for a

00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:10.480
<v Speaker 1>What if we say the cars?

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:11.600
<v Speaker 1>Los carros.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:12.240
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:13.600
<v Speaker 1>Los carros.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:16.240
<v Speaker 1>So the plural of el is los.

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:17.920
<v Speaker 1>It's a little bit different.

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:18.800
<v Speaker 1>El to los

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:23.280
<v Speaker 1>The word for expensive is caro.

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:26.640
<v Speaker 1>So it's like caro but with one R.

00:01:26.799 --> 00:01:27.840
<v Speaker 1>Caro.

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:28.380
<v Speaker 2>Caro.

00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:40.540
<v Speaker 1>So again it's a nice pair to feel the difference between having the single R and the double R, just as we saw in pero meaning but and pero meaning dog.

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.720
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say the car is expensive?

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:47.520
<v Speaker 2>El carro is caro.

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:48.240
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:51.040
<v Speaker 1>El carro is caro good

00:01:52.340 --> 00:02:02.259
<v Speaker 1>So S we said was it is, she is, he is, or just is, or you are talking to usted, talking formally.

00:02:02.259 --> 00:02:04.979
<v Speaker 1>So if you just wanted to say it is expensive

00:02:05.840 --> 00:02:06.719
<v Speaker 2>Escara.

00:02:06.719 --> 00:02:06.960
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:10.080
<v Speaker 1>And what if you're talking about a feminine thing?

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:11.440
<v Speaker 2>Escara.

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:12.319
<v Speaker 1>Escara.

00:02:12.319 --> 00:02:19.519
<v Speaker 1>And when I say feminine thing I really mean a feminine noun, if you're referring in your mind to a feminine noun because

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:26.720
<v Speaker 1>If you in your country call cars machinas, then you're gonna say escara.

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:28.560
<v Speaker 1>But if you call them autos

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:30.420
<v Speaker 1>then you're gonna say escaro.

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:35.540
<v Speaker 1>So it refers to the word more than the object, to the noun, the gender of the noun.

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:38.660
<v Speaker 1>So s we have for is and

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:48.760
<v Speaker 1>For they are or you guys are we know they always come together, we have son, son, s-on.

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:53.240
<v Speaker 1>So if you want to say the cars are expensive

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:55.480
<v Speaker 1>And we will use carro again.

00:02:55.480 --> 00:02:59.560
<v Speaker 1>So the cars are expensive.

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:03.000
<v Speaker 2>Los carros son caro

00:03:03.480 --> 00:03:05.000
<v Speaker 2>Uh caros.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:05.560
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:08.200
<v Speaker 1>Los carros son carros.

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:09.160
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:12.040
<v Speaker 1>What if you use a feminine word like maquina?

00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:13.000
<v Speaker 1>How is it gonna be?

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.400
<v Speaker 1>The cars are expensive.

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:19.000
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.840
<v Speaker 1>Las machinas son caras.

00:03:20.840 --> 00:03:25.080
<v Speaker 1>And the car is expensive using again machina.

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:28.540
<v Speaker 2>La machina es caro.

00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:29.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:31.420
<v Speaker 1>La maquina es cara.

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:37.019
<v Speaker 1>The word teacher in Spanish is profesor, profesor.

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:37.880
<v Speaker 1>Profesor.

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:38.920
<v Speaker 1>Profesor.

00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:41.720
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say he is a professor?

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:45.480
<v Speaker 1>And we don't need to say A, we can just say he is Professor

00:03:46.700 --> 00:03:47.900
<v Speaker 2>Es profesor.

00:03:47.900 --> 00:03:48.379
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:48.379 --> 00:03:50.299
<v Speaker 1>Es profesor.

00:03:50.299 --> 00:03:53.340
<v Speaker 1>What if you wanted to say she is a professor?

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:55.500
<v Speaker 1>What do you think might happen?

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.360
<v Speaker 2>Es profesora?

00:03:58.599 --> 00:03:59.159
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:59.159 --> 00:04:00.439
<v Speaker 1>Es profesora.

00:04:00.439 --> 00:04:06.280
<v Speaker 1>What if you wanted to say they are teachers and you mean a group of females?

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:09.360
<v Speaker 2>Son profesoras.

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:11.360
<v Speaker 1>Son profesoras.

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:12.720
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:15.120
<v Speaker 1>So this is a noun.

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:16.280
<v Speaker 1>Professor.

00:04:16.280 --> 00:04:19.959
<v Speaker 1>It's a word you can put the or a in front of.

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:25.560
<v Speaker 1>Now we said that adjectives they change for gender if they end in o

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:27.040
<v Speaker 1>If they don't they don't.

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:34.800
<v Speaker 1>For example the global situation was La Global Situation.

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:36.800
<v Speaker 1>Where does that global go?

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:40.340
<v Speaker 2>Ah, la situation global.

00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:42.100
<v Speaker 1>La situation global.

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:45.700
<v Speaker 1>So situation is feminine, but we're not saying globala.

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:53.280
<v Speaker 1>Adjectives, these describing words that we can put is in front of, they only change if they end in o.

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:54.240
<v Speaker 1>But nouns

00:04:54.740 --> 00:05:00.500
<v Speaker 1>They can change to feminine like profesor, profesora to differentiate.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:02.100
<v Speaker 1>So this is why it's important

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:05.640
<v Speaker 1>to know what type of word we're dealing with.

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:08.280
<v Speaker 1>We're doing this already, but we don't even realize it.

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:11.560
<v Speaker 1>The moment we come in contact with a verb, we know exactly what to do.

00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:14.920
<v Speaker 1>We know it's a verb and we know how to manage it.

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:19.259
<v Speaker 1>We don't start trying to make a verb masculine or feminine, for example.

00:05:19.259 --> 00:05:24.379
<v Speaker 1>So we're already making this differentiation, but we want to do it more consciously to get more control.

00:05:24.379 --> 00:05:25.740
<v Speaker 1>So this is a noun

00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:28.220
<v Speaker 1>Doctor, what do you think that means?

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:29.020
<v Speaker 2>Doctor.

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:29.660
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:30.540
<v Speaker 1>Is it a noun?

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:31.420
<v Speaker 1>Is it an adjective?

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:32.140
<v Speaker 1>Is it a verb?

00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:33.340
<v Speaker 1>What is it?

00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:34.540
<v Speaker 2>Noun.

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:35.100
<v Speaker 1>Noun.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:39.420
<v Speaker 1>So how do you think feminine a female doctor would be?

00:05:39.660 --> 00:05:40.620
<v Speaker 2>Doctora?

00:05:40.620 --> 00:05:41.020
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:41.820
<v Speaker 1>Doctora.

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:43.020
<v Speaker 1>We just stick an A.

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:43.340
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:45.740
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say he is a doctor?

00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:47.980
<v Speaker 2>S Doctor.

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:48.380
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:49.740
<v Speaker 1>She is a doctor

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:52.100
<v Speaker 2>As doctor.

00:05:52.100 --> 00:05:52.900
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:52.900 --> 00:06:02.500
<v Speaker 1>Now if you want to get the plural of professor, professor, or doctor, doctor, or any other word

00:06:02.940 --> 00:06:08.940
<v Speaker 1>in Spanish that ends in a consonant, you don't add s, you add es.

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:12.780
<v Speaker 1>So how do you think it would sound the plural of profesor

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:14.940
<v Speaker 1>Professores.

00:06:14.940 --> 00:06:15.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:17.020
<v Speaker 1>Professores.

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:21.260
<v Speaker 1>So this is the plural for masculine or for mixed.

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:22.860
<v Speaker 1>The plural for feminine

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:24.620
<v Speaker 2>Profesores.

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:25.420
<v Speaker 2>Good.

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:27.260
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say they are professors?

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:31.340
<v Speaker 1>And you mean a masculine or mixed group?

00:06:31.340 --> 00:06:33.420
<v Speaker 2>Son profesores.

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:33.820
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:35.100
<v Speaker 1>Son profesores.

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:37.740
<v Speaker 1>And if they were all female?

00:06:38.700 --> 00:06:40.140
<v Speaker 2>Son professoras.

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:40.620
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:40.620 --> 00:06:45.020
<v Speaker 1>They are doctors mixed or masculine?

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:46.780
<v Speaker 1>Son doctores.

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:47.340
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:48.700
<v Speaker 1>Son doctores.

00:06:48.700 --> 00:06:50.940
<v Speaker 1>What if they were females?

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:52.780
<v Speaker 2>Son doctoras.

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:53.180
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:53.180 --> 00:06:54.620
<v Speaker 1>Son doctoras.

00:06:54.620 --> 00:06:55.340
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:55.340 --> 00:06:59.660
<v Speaker 1>Words ending I V E in English

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:07.380
<v Speaker 1>I V E tend to become Ivo IVO for masculine singular.

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:13.620
<v Speaker 1>This is the one we always start from now and build from this masculine singular or neutral, let's say

00:07:13.660 --> 00:07:16.860
<v Speaker 1>So for example addictive becomes addictivo.

00:07:16.860 --> 00:07:20.300
<v Speaker 1>Now when I say neuta, we don't really have a neuta in Spanish.

00:07:20.300 --> 00:07:21.980
<v Speaker 1>We have masculine and feminine.

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:24.300
<v Speaker 1>But the concept of neuta exists.

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:26.940
<v Speaker 1>Let's say for example if I say it's addictive

00:07:27.039 --> 00:07:32.319
<v Speaker 1>And I'm referring to living in the mountains is addictive.

00:07:32.319 --> 00:07:34.319
<v Speaker 1>Eating healthily is addictive.

00:07:34.319 --> 00:07:35.120
<v Speaker 1>Or something like this.

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:36.800
<v Speaker 1>Then I use the masculine singular.

00:07:36.800 --> 00:07:39.520
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say it's addictive?

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:41.139
<v Speaker 1>Es adictivo.

00:07:41.139 --> 00:07:41.539
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:07:41.539 --> 00:07:42.900
<v Speaker 1>Es adictivo.

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:46.020
<v Speaker 1>How would you say he is positive?

00:07:46.659 --> 00:07:47.699
<v Speaker 2>Es positivo.

00:07:47.699 --> 00:07:52.099
<v Speaker 1>Good, and you pronounce an S where most English speakers will probably find themselves

00:07:52.160 --> 00:08:03.040
<v Speaker 1>pronouncing a Z there because in English we have positive positive so that would probably transfer into Spanish to positivo and we want to be careful not to do that.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:05.600
<v Speaker 1>Positivo with a S positivo

00:08:06.139 --> 00:08:08.460
<v Speaker 1>She is positive?

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:09.660
<v Speaker 1>Is positiva.

00:08:09.660 --> 00:08:10.460
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:10.460 --> 00:08:12.780
<v Speaker 1>They are positive.

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:14.060
<v Speaker 2>Son positivos.

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:14.540
<v Speaker 2>Good.

00:08:14.540 --> 00:08:16.860
<v Speaker 1>They are intuitive.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:19.500
<v Speaker 2>Son intuitivos.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:20.060
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:21.420
<v Speaker 1>Son intuitivos.

00:08:21.420 --> 00:08:23.900
<v Speaker 1>What if you meant women?

00:08:24.220 --> 00:08:25.340
<v Speaker 2>Intuitivas.

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:25.660
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:27.500
<v Speaker 1>Son intuitivas.

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:30.460
<v Speaker 1>She is very attractive.

00:08:30.460 --> 00:08:35.260
<v Speaker 1>The word for very is mui and it's spelt M-U-Y.

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:38.300
<v Speaker 1>The Y you can imagine it like an I, MUI.

00:08:38.300 --> 00:08:39.180
<v Speaker 2>MUI.

00:08:39.180 --> 00:08:39.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:39.580 --> 00:08:41.900
<v Speaker 1>So she is very attractive.

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:46.340
<v Speaker 2>Es muy attractivo.

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:49.060
<v Speaker 2>Oh attractiva.

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:50.020
<v Speaker 1>Attractiva.

00:08:50.340 --> 00:08:52.100
<v Speaker 2>Es muy attractiva.

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:52.660
<v Speaker 1>Good

00:08:52.920 --> 00:09:06.120
<v Speaker 1>atractiva is uh showing us that it refers to a female so this would probably help us work out who we're talking about but maybe we would want to say it to clarify or to emphasize or to contrast

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:09.100
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say that using the word for she?

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:12.060
<v Speaker 1>She is very attractive.

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:13.900
<v Speaker 2>I always get confused on that.

00:09:13.900 --> 00:09:17.580
<v Speaker 2>If it's el or if it's uh la or ella.

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:21.480
<v Speaker 1>So I want you to spend some time to think about it and not guess.

00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:24.360
<v Speaker 1>Think about which is which and make a decision

00:09:24.959 --> 00:09:26.240
<v Speaker 2>Her is la.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:27.120
<v Speaker 2>Good.

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:30.160
<v Speaker 2>Ella is muy attractiva.

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:30.800
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:33.440
<v Speaker 1>Ella is muy attractiva.

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:36.399
<v Speaker 1>How do you say she is very creative?

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:43.680
<v Speaker 1>Ella es muy creativa, but she's aggressive.

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:45.120
<v Speaker 2>Pero es

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:46.920
<v Speaker 2>Is it agresiva?

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:48.360
<v Speaker 2>I was thinking of the double G.

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:56.440
<v Speaker 1>Does it stay Ah well these random double letters that we don't need in English really, they just become single letters in Spanish.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:09:59.480
<v Speaker 1>So I think there's a double S there as well in English.

00:09:58.959 --> 00:10:01.040
<v Speaker 1>Well that would also become singular.

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:05.360
<v Speaker 1>The only double letters that cross over are the Rs and the N's.

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:07.120
<v Speaker 1>Like connotacion.

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:08.160
<v Speaker 2>And double Ns is.

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:09.920
<v Speaker 1>Connotacion.

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:17.020
<v Speaker 1>If you get a double F, double S, double G, these random double letters you get in English, they don't cross over into Spanish.

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:21.420
<v Speaker 1>How would you say they are aggressive talking about a masculine or a mixed group?

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:24.180
<v Speaker 2>Son agresivos.

00:10:24.180 --> 00:10:24.820
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:28.660
<v Speaker 1>And what if you wanted to use the word for they?

00:10:28.980 --> 00:10:31.540
<v Speaker 2>Ellos son agresivos.

00:10:31.540 --> 00:10:32.100
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:10:32.100 --> 00:10:35.220
<v Speaker 1>How would you say he is negative?

00:10:35.899 --> 00:10:37.180
<v Speaker 2>Es negativo.

00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:37.500
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:40.620
<v Speaker 1>And if you use the word for he?

00:10:40.620 --> 00:10:42.699
<v Speaker 2>El is negativo.

00:10:42.699 --> 00:10:43.180
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:10:43.180 --> 00:10:45.980
<v Speaker 1>He's very negative.

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:48.120
<v Speaker 2>Es muy negativo.

00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:50.519
<v Speaker 1>How would you say it's intensive?

00:10:50.519 --> 00:10:53.160
<v Speaker 1>It's intensive.

00:10:54.180 --> 00:10:55.380
<v Speaker 2>intensivo.

00:10:55.380 --> 00:10:55.940
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:10:55.940 --> 00:10:58.420
<v Speaker 1>So we we use the neuter there.

00:10:58.420 --> 00:10:59.860
<v Speaker 1>We don't know what we're talking about.

00:10:59.860 --> 00:11:04.020
<v Speaker 1>So we can just use the masculine singular which is also like neutr.

00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:06.100
<v Speaker 1>S intensivo.

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:10.320
<v Speaker 1>How would you say they are natives?

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:13.600
<v Speaker 1>They are natives.

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:15.120
